<div id=3D"a">
<div id=3D"circle" style=3D"background-color: rgb(225, 255, 246);"></div><h=
2>What is the Area of a Kite?</h2>
</div>
<p>The area of a kite can be defined as the amount of space enclosed or enc=
ompassed by a kite in a two-dimensional plane. Like a <a href=3D"https://ww=
w.cuemath.com/geometry/square/">square</a>, and a <a href=3D"https://www.cu=
emath.com/geometry/rhombus/">rhombus</a>, a kite does not have all four sid=
es equal. The area of a kite is always expressed in terms of units<sup>2</s=
up> for example, in<sup>2</sup>, cm<sup>2</sup>, m<sup>2</sup>, etc. Let us=
 learn about the area of a kite formula in our next section.</p>
<div id=3D"b">
<div id=3D"circle" style=3D"background-color: rgb(225, 255, 246);"></div><h=
2>Area of a Kite Formula</h2>
</div>
<p>The area of a kite is half the product of the lengths of its <a href=3D"=
https://www.cuemath.com/geometry/diagonals/">diagonals</a>. The formula to =
determine the area of a kite is: Area =3D =C2=BD =C3=97 (d)<sub>1</sub> =C3=
=97 (d)<sub>2</sub>. Here (d)<sub>1</sub> and (d)<sub>2</sub> are long and =
short diagonals of a kite.<br>
The area of kite ABCD given below is =C2=BD =C3=97 AC =C3=97 BD.</p>
<p><img alt=3D"Area of Kite" src=3D"https://d138zd1ktt9iqe.cloudfront.net/m=
edia/seo_landing_files/area-of-kite-1624862434.png" style=3D"width: 400px;"=
></p>
<p>BD =3D Long diagonal and AC =3D Short diagonal</p>
<div id=3D"c">
<div id=3D"circle" style=3D"background-color: rgb(225, 255, 246);"></div><h=
2>Derivation of the Area of Kite Formula</h2>
</div>
<p>Consider a kite ABCD as shown above.</p>
<p>Assume the lengths of the diagonals of ABCD to be AC =3D p, BD =3D q</p>
<p>We know that the longer diagonal of a kite bisects the shorter diagonal =
at right angles, i.e., BD bisects AC and =E2=88=A0AOB =3D 90=C2=B0, =E2=88=
=A0BOC =3D 90=C2=B0.</p>
<p>Therefore,</p>
<p>AO =3D OC =3D AC/2 =3D p/2</p>
<p>Area of kite ABCD =3D Area of =CE=94ABD + Area of =CE=94BCD...(1)</p>
<p>We know that,</p>
<p>Area of a triangle =3D =C2=BD =C3=97 Base =C3=97 Height</p>
<p>Now, we will calculate the areas of triangles ABD and BCD</p>
<p>Area of =CE=94ABD =3D =C2=BD =C3=97 AO =C3=97 BD =3D =C2=BD =C3=97 p/2 =
=C3=97 q =3D (pq)/4</p>
<p>Area of =CE=94BCD =3D =C2=BD =C3=97 OC =C3=97 BD =3D =C2=BD =C3=97 p/2 =
=C3=97 q =3D (pq)/4</p>
<p>Therefore, using (1)</p>
<p>Area of kite ABCD =3D (pq)/4 + (pq)/4<br>
=3D (pq)/2<br>
Substituting the values of p and q<br>
Area of a kite =3D =C2=BD =C3=97 AC =C3=97 BD</p>
